# t/research/archive-dedup.test — archival is content-addressed (decision-013): a
# blob is stored ONCE regardless of how many tasks archive it, while each task keeps
# its own archive index row and resolves its own file's bytes.
#
# Before this, the archive stored `bytes` inline per row, so the whole memory
# collection provisioned into every run was duplicated into every task's archive —
# unbounded growth (tasks × collection). Now AddArchive stores the bytes once in the
# blob table keyed by sha256 and inserts a per-task index row referencing it. Two
# tasks that both archive the SAME provisioned memory file share ONE blob but keep
# TWO index rows.

send allow-sender { address kasi@decode.ee }

# Seed a durable memory. start-agent-run provisions the whole collection into every
# future run's in/memory/ box, so BOTH tasks below get owner-banking.md laid in with
# byte-identical content — the shared content the dedup collapses.
memory write owner-banking [fixture memory/owner-banking.md]

# --- Task 1: finishes, then the owner clicks completion → archive-then-delete. ---
deliver {
    from    kasi@decode.ee
    to      research@kasi.test
    subject "one"
    body    "first task"
}
task 1 status is awaiting-agent
# The seeded memory is provisioned into this run.
task 1 input memory/owner-banking.md matches "*Handelsbanken*"

agent {
    out reply.txt "done one"
}
task 1 status is awaiting-user
click [outbound last completion-link]
task 1 status is done

# --- Task 2: a brand-new task, gets the SAME memory provisioned, archives it too. ---
deliver {
    from    kasi@decode.ee
    to      research@kasi.test
    subject "two"
    body    "second task"
}
task 2 status is awaiting-agent
task 2 input memory/owner-banking.md matches "*Handelsbanken*"

agent {
    out reply.txt "done two"
}
task 2 status is awaiting-user
click [outbound last completion-link]
task 2 status is done

# --- Dedup proof: one blob, two index rows for the shared memory file. ---
# The provisioned note is byte-identical across both tasks, so it is stored ONCE...
archive blobs in/memory/owner-banking.md is 1
# ...yet BOTH tasks' archive indexes list it (one row each).
archive rows in/memory/owner-banking.md is 2
# The MEMORY.md index käsi lays in (at the in/ box root) is likewise identical
# across tasks — one blob, two index rows.
archive blobs in/MEMORY.md is 1
archive rows in/MEMORY.md is 2

# Each task still resolves its OWN file's bytes back through the blob JOIN — the
# dedup is invisible at the read boundary.
archive task 1 file in/memory/owner-banking.md matches "*Handelsbanken*"
archive task 2 file in/memory/owner-banking.md matches "*never reuse an OCR*"

# Sanity: each task's transcript is unique (run-tagged), so those are NOT deduped —
# dedup collapses identical content, it does not lose distinct content.
archive count task 1 transcript is 1
archive count task 2 transcript is 1
